<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>In the money market, what happens when new financial technology reduces the amount of money people need to hold?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Money demand shifts right, interest rates rise</option>
            <option letter="b">Money demand shifts left, interest rates fall</option>
            <option letter="c">Money supply shifts right, interest rates fall</option>
            <option letter="d">Money supply shifts left, interest rates rise</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When financial technology (like digital payments) makes it easier to conduct transactions with less cash, people need to hold less money at every interest rate. This shifts the money demand curve left, resulting in lower equilibrium interest rates while the money supply remains constant.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
